# SCM syntax highlighting & preventing 3-way merges
pixi.lock merge=binary linguist-language=YAML linguist-generated=true -diff

# M21 Phase 5 (#242): gofmt is byte-strict about LF-only line endings. Without this, a Windows
# checkout of src/Aer.Sidecar (Windows git's default core.autocrlf converts LF blobs to CRLF on
# checkout) makes `gofmt -l .` report an already-clean file as needing formatting -- found live via
# CI's Windows job failing fmt-check-sidecar despite an identical Linux job passing.
*.go text eol=lf
src/Aer.Sidecar/go.mod text eol=lf
src/Aer.Sidecar/go.sum text eol=lf

# Shell scripts and patch files must stay LF on every platform. A CRLF shell script fails on
# Linux with `bash: \r: command not found` on its first line, and `git apply` rejects a CRLF
# patch against LF sources -- both would break CI's Linux jobs while passing on Windows.
*.sh text eol=lf
*.patch -text

# tools/ui-harness is Windows-only by construction (user32/dwmapi P/Invoke against a running
# Avalonia window), so CRLF is the native convention here. Pinned explicitly rather than left to
# core.autocrlf so the checkout is identical regardless of a contributor's git config -- same
# reasoning as the LF pins above, which were both added after a line-ending difference broke a
# build that passed locally.
*.ps1 text eol=crlf
